Working with pseudo-classes
Pseudo-classes
Used to define a special state of an element.
Elements, much like most objects can exist in different states.
 
#Why use pseudo-classes?
1.Enables improved navigation for end-user.
2.Conveys meaning to selected elements.
3.Enhances user interface.

##common pseudo-classes
Common Pseudo-classes

1) :active
Example: a:active
Details: Selects the active link

2) :hover
Example: a:hover
Details: Selects links on mouse over

3) :link
Example: a:link
Details: Selects all unvisited links

4) :visited
Example: a:visited
Details: Selects all visited links

5) :focus
Example: input:focus
Details: Selects the input element which has focus

6) :checked
Example: input:checked
Details: Selects every checked <input> element

7) :disabled
Example: input:disabled
Details: Selects every disabled <input> element

8) :first-child
Example: p:first-child
Details: Selects every <p> element that is the first child of its parent

9) :invalid
Example: input:invalid
Details: Selects all input elements with an invalid value




